Assistant:You call `thing2()`, so `item` in `thing2` gets its default value `nil`. Which it then gives to `thing`. So `item` in `thing` is `nil` as well. If you want it to be `"yeah"` instead, then you need to call `thing` truly *without* a value for `item`. Not with the `nil` value.

One way to do that would be to use a hash parameter instead of the keyword argument:

```
def thing(item: "yeah")
  puts item == nil
end  
def thing2(options = {})
  thing(options)
end
thing2()
thing2(item: nil)

```

That prints `false` for `thing2()` because `thing2` doesn't get an `item` value and thus doesn't give an `item` value to `thing`. So `thing` uses the default `"yeah"`.

And it prints `true` for `thing2(item: nil)` because `thing2` does get an `item` value and forwards it to `thing`, and it's `nil`.

Not sure whether that's a good idea, I guess it depends on your actual use case.

Edit: As @SergioTulentsev commented, you can also still use keyword arguments:

```
def thing(item: "yeah")
  puts item == nil
end  
def thing2(**kwargs)
  thing(**kwargs)
end
thing2()
thing2(item: nil)

```

That's probably better, consistently using keyword arguments everywhere.

