 Assistant: Step 1: First, let's simplify the expression inside the summation by using the formula for the sum of a geometric series:

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2^k}+\frac{1}{3^k}+\cdots+\frac{1}{n^k} &= \frac{1}{2^k} \left(1 + \left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^{-k} + \cdots + \left(\frac{n}{2}\right)^{-k}\right) \\
&\quad + \frac{1}{3^k} \left(\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^k + 1 + \cdots + \left(\frac{n}{3}\right)^{-k}\right) \\
&\quad + \cdots \\
&\quad + \frac{1}{n^k} \left(\left(\frac{n}{2}\right)^k + \left(\frac{n}{3}\right)^k + \cdots + 1\right) \\
&= \sum_{j=2}^{n} \frac{1}{j^k} \sum_{i=j}^{n} \left(\frac{i}{j}\right)^{-k}
\end{align*}

Step 2: We can now substitute this expression back into the original summation:

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=2}^\infty\Bigl\{
\frac{1}{2^k}+\frac{1}{3^k}+\cdots+\frac{1}{n^k}
\Bigr\} &= \sum_{k=2}^\infty \sum_{j=2}^{n} \frac{1}{j^k} \sum_{i=j}^{n} \left(\frac{i}{j}\right)^{-k} \\
&= \sum_{j=2}^{n} \sum_{k=2}^\infty \frac{1}{j^k} \sum_{i=j}^{n} \left(\frac{i}{j}\right)^{-k}
\end{align*}

Step 3: We can now interchange the order of summation, since all the terms are positive:

\begin{align*}
\sum_{j=2}^{n} \sum_{k=2}^\infty \frac{1}{j^k} \sum_{i=j}^{n} \left(\frac{i}{j}\right)^{-k} &= \sum_{i=2}^{n} \sum_{j=2}^{i} \sum_{k=2}^\infty \frac{1}{j^k} \left(\frac{i}{j}\right)^{-k} \\
&= \sum_{i=2}^{n} \sum_{j=2}^{i} \frac{1}{j^2} \sum_{k=0}^\infty \left(\frac{i}{j}\right)^{-k} - 1 \\
&= \sum_{i=2}^{n} \sum_{j=2}^{i} \frac{1}{j^2} \frac{1}{1 - \frac{i}{j}} - 1 \\
&= \sum_{i=2}^{n} \sum_{j=2}^{i} \frac{1}{j(i-j)} - 1 \\
&= \sum_{i=2}^{n} \sum_{j=2}^{i} \left(\frac{1}{j} + \frac{1}{i-j}\right) - 1 \\
&= \sum_{i=2}^{n} \left(\frac{i-1}{i}\right) - 1 \\
&= \boxed{1 - \frac{1}{n}}
\end{align*}

